font-size:14pt;padding-bottom:4pt;font-family:"Arial";line-height:1.15;page-break-after:avoid;orphans:2;widows:2;text-align:left}h4{padding-top:14pt;color:#666666;font-size:12pt;padding-bottom:4pt;font-family:"Arial";line-height:1.15;page-break-after:avoid;orphans:2;widows:2;text-align:left}h5{padding-top:12pt;color:#666666;font-size:11pt;padding-bottom:4pt;font-family:"Arial";line-height:1.15;page-break-after:avoid;orphans:2;widows:2;text-align:left}h6{padding-top:12pt;color:#666666;font-size:11pt;padding-bottom:4pt;font-family:"Arial";line-height:1.15;page-break-after:avoid;font-style:italic;orphans:2;widows:2;text-align:left}</style></head><body class="c31 c96 doc-content"><div><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p></div><h1 class="c23 c25" id="h.dotnno6j1us1"><span class="c22">Algorithmic trading</span></h1><p class="c16 c23"><span class="c11">&nbsp;</span></p><a id="t.df18a5edbdc2c8cfc46759c76dfc58a4a9a13abc"></a><a id="t.0"></a><table class="c26"><tr class="c4"><td class="c70" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><h2 class="c23 c27" id="h.cfe7k84p0c8a"><span class="c1">Content </span></h2><p class="c16 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><a id="t.8938ad8dcf1f86b0f915ba9512a6d4e1b147ec1a"></a><a id="t.1"></a><table class="c26"><tr class="c4"><td class="c21" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><h2 class="c27 c23 c57" id="h.yklgp4a6uoq3"><span class="c1"></span></h2><p class="c16 c23"><span class="c11">1 ________________________________________________________History</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">1.1 Early developments </span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">1.2 Refinement and growth </span></p><p class="c16 c23"><span class="c11">2________________________________________________________Strategies</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">2.1 Systematic Trading</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">2.2 Trading ahead of index fund rebalancing</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">2.3 Pairs trading</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">2.4 Delta-neutral strategies</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">2.5 Arbitrage</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">2.5.1 Conditions for arbitrage</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">2.6 Mean reversion</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">2.7 Scalping</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">2.8 Transaction cost reduction</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">2.9 Strategies that only pertain to dark pools</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">2.10 Market timing</span></p><p class="c16 c23"><span class="c11">3______________________________________________________High-frequency trading</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">3.1 Market making</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">3.2 Statistical arbitrage</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">3.3 Event arbitrage</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">3.4 Spoofing</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">3.5 Quote stuffing</span></p><p class="c16 c23"><span class="c11">4_________________________________________________Low latency trading systems</span></p><p class="c16 c23"><span class="c11">5_____________________________________________________Strategy implementation</span></p><p class="c16 c23 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><a id="t.7ad46881c3e664a57a95d56890e2bd9718a7e0bf"></a><a id="t.2"></a><table class="c83"><tr class="c4"><td class="c61" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c16 c23"><span class="c11">6_____________________________________Issues and developments</span></p><p class="c16 c23 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><a id="t.2a7ab31d244d5ffcf368a314c6feaaa4db96c161"></a><a id="t.3"></a><table class="c26"><tr class="c4"><td class="c59" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c7"><span class="c11">6.1 Cyborg finance</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">6.2 Concerns</span></p><p class="c7"><span class="c11">6.3 Recent developments</span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c16 c23 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c16 c13 c23"><span class="c11"></span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c16 c23 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c7 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c16 c23"><span class="c11">7 &nbsp;_________________________________________________System architecture</span></p><p class="c16 c23"><span class="c11">8 &nbsp;_________________________________________________Automated controls</span></p><p class="c16 c23"><span class="c11">9 &nbsp;________________________________________________Effects</span></p><p class="c16 c23"><span class="c11">10 ______________________________________________Communication standards</span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c16 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c13 c16"><span class="c11"></span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c9"><span class="c11">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="c9"><span>&nbsp;</span><hr style="page-break-before:always;display:none;"></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c68 c23 c13 title" id="h.7jrmjsff1zhy"><span class="c37"></span></p><a id="t.702db310bc6adf2a9cfc7addad64b69527a10286"></a><a id="t.4"></a><table class="c26"><tr class="c4"><td class="c70" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><h1 class="c60" id="h.94ixs4wzldmf"><span class="c22">Introduction</span></h1><a id="t.d86a33e7230d76ccfc66fd1b4acc17368067f3ff"></a><a id="t.5"></a><table class="c26"><tr class="c4"><td class="c21" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c9"><span class="c11">Algorithmic trading is a type of automated trading that relies on pre-programmed rules to execute orders as quickly as possible. It attempts to increase the speed of computer transactions relative to human traders, who may be slower and more prone to error. Some investors use algorithmic trading because it allows them to place large orders without the time and expense associated with manually executing those trades themselves. Studies have shown that around 92% of trading in the Forex market is performed by algorithms rather than humans; many banks and other financial institutions also use algorithms in their operations.</span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c11">The term &quot;algorithmic trading&quot; is often used to describe automated trading systems, which encompass a variety of trading strategies and rely on specialized software. These strategies include systematic trading, market making, intermarket spreading, arbitrage, or pure speculation such as trend following.</span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c11">High-frequency trading (HFT) is characterised by high turnover and high order-to-trade ratios. HFT strategies utilise computers that make elaborate decisions to initiate orders based on information that is received electronically, before human traders are capable of processing the information they observe. The Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC) formed a special working group in February 2012 to advise them on how best to define HFT. In doing so, they discovered that algorithmic trading and HFT had resulted in a dramatic change of the market microstructure and in the complexity and uncertainty of the market macrodynamic&mdash;particularly in terms of liquidity provision.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c11">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c11">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c11">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="c23 c13 c68 title" id="h.z1sykvse1b1m"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c16 c13"><span class="c37"></span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c16 c13"><span class="c37"></span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c68 c23 c13 title" id="h.b8jh6yyepu93"><span class="c37"></span></p><h1 class="c69 c23 c79" id="h.9zqugdmvk37o"><span class="c22"></span></h1><a id="t.a9ba7f91f05958d98d0dd245d04a23a309afc7db"></a><a id="t.6"></a><table class="c65"><tr class="c4"><td class="c70" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><h1 class="c69 c23" id="h.v6ai1tjzfji"><span class="c22">Early developments</span></h1><p class="c16 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><a id="t.2a28bfaea20f1a6ec9073b0182bcea1ba5734772"></a><a id="t.7"></a><table class="c26"><tr class="c4"><td class="c21" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c9"><span class="c11">The rise of fully electronic markets in the early 1970s led to the development of the designated order turnaround system (DOT) by the New York Stock Exchange. SuperDOT was introduced in 1984 as an upgraded version of DOT, which allowed for the routing of orders electronically to the proper trading post. In the 1980s, program trading became widely used in trading between the S&amp;P 500 equity and futures markets&mdash;known as index arbitrage&mdash;as an automated strategy that focused on capturing profit opportunities by buying when prices were low and selling when prices were high.</span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c11">In 1987, at about the same time as portfolio insurance was created, computer-driven trading strategies were developed that could create synthetic put options on stock portfolios based on a computer model based on the Black&ndash;Scholes option pricing model. These strategies were blamed by many people for exacerbating or even starting the 1987 stock market crash. The impact of these trading strategies on stock market crashes is unclear and widely discussed in academic circles.</span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c16 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p></td></tr></table><h1 class="c69 c23 c79" id="h.ukmb3eq1m34w"><span class="c22"></span></h1><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><hr style="page-break-before:always;display:none;"><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><a id="t.9aae8a0174ae28c3fb8ac84ade38abe54e40b78b"></a><a id="t.8"></a><table class="c26"><tr class="c4"><td class="c70" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><h1 class="c23 c69" id="h.laqqcyhjt5tv"><span class="c22">Refinement and growth</span></h1><p class="c16 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><a id="t.68bd7ebf414bfb584728e92514df69ef2d17ed8f"></a><a id="t.9"></a><table class="c26"><tr class="c4"><td class="c21" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c9"><span class="c11">In the 1990s, electronic communication networks (ECNs) were introduced to the financial markets. These networks allow investors to trade stocks and currencies outside of traditional exchanges. Beginning in 2001, the minimum tick size on U.S. stock exchanges was reduced from US$0.0625 per share to US$0.01 per share, which may have encouraged algorithmic trading as it changed market microstructure by permitting smaller differences between bid and offer prices, decreasing market-makers&#39; trading advantage.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c11">This increased market liquidity led to institutional traders splitting up orders according to computer algorithms so they could execute orders at a better average price. In doing so, they abandoned the use of volume-weighted averages in favour of time-weighted averages, which measure the average price over a specific period of time.</span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c11">A further encouragement for the adoption of algorithmic trading in the financial markets came in 2001 when a team of IBM researchers published a paper at the International Joint Conference on Artificial Intelligence where they showed that in experimental laboratory versions of the electronic auctions used in the financial markets, two algorithmic strategies (IBM&#39;s own MGD, and Hewlett-Packard&#39;s ZIP) could consistently out-perform human traders. MGD was a modified version of the &quot;GD&quot; algorithm invented by Steven Gjerstad &amp; John Dickhaut in 1996 the ZIP algorithm had been invented at HP by Dave Cliff (professor) in 1996.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c11">In their 2005 paper, the IBM team wrote that their results showing MGD and ZIP outperforming human traders &quot;...might be measured in billions of dollars annually&quot;; this generated international media coverage.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c11">As more electronic markets opened, other algorithmic trading strategies were introduced. Computers could react rapidly to price changes and observe several markets simultaneously. Many broker-dealers offered these strategies to their clients - differentiating them by behaviour, options and branding. Examples include Chameleon (developed by BNP Paribas), Stealth (developed by the Deutsche Bank), Sniper and Guerilla (developed by Credit Suisse). These implementations adopted practices from the investing approaches of arbitrage, statistical arbitrage, trend following and mean reversion.</span></p><p class="c23 c64"><span class="c11">Case studies Profitability projections by the TABB Group, a financial services industry research firm, for the US equities HFT industry were US$1.3 billion before expenses for 2014, significantly down on the maximum of US$21 billion that the 300 securities firms and hedge funds that then specialised in this type of trading took in profits in 2008, which the authors had then called &quot;relatively small&quot; and &quot;surprisingly modest&quot; when compared to the market&#39;s overall trading volume.</span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c11">In March 2014, Virtu Financial, a high-frequency trading firm, reported that during five years the firm as a whole was profitable on 1,277 out of 1,278 trading days, losing money just one day, demonstrating the benefits of trading millions of times, across a diverse set of instruments every trading day.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c11">Algorithmic trading. Percentage of market volume.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c11">A third of all European Union and United States stock trades in 2006 were driven by automatic programs, or algorithms. As of 2009, studies suggested HFT firms accounted for 60&ndash;73% of all US equity trading volume, with that number falling to approximately 50% in 2012. In 2006, at the London Stock Exchange, over 40% of all orders were entered by algorithmic traders, with 60% predicted for 2007. American markets and European markets generally have a higher proportion of algorithmic trades than other markets, and estimates for 2008 range as high as an 80% proportion in some markets. Foreign exchange markets also have active algorithmic trading, measured at about 80% of orders in 2016 (up from about 25% of orders in 2006).Futures markets are considered fairly easy to integrate into algorithmic trading, with about 20% of options volume expected to be computer-generated by 2010. Bond markets are moving toward more access to algorithmic traders.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c11">Algorithmic trading and HFT have been the subject of much public debate since the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and the Commodity Futures Trading Commission said in reports that an algorithmic trade entered by a mutual fund company triggered a wave of selling that led to the 2010 Flash Crash.The same reports found HFT strategies may have contributed to subsequent volatility by rapidly pulling liquidity from the market. As a result of these events, the Dow Jones Industrial Average suffered its second largest intraday point swing ever to that date, though prices quickly recovered. (See List of largest daily changes in the Dow Jones Industrial Average.) A July 2011 report by the International Organisation of Securities Commissions (IOSCO), an international body of securities regulators, concluded that while &quot;algorithms and HFT technology have been used by market participants to manage their trading and risk, their usage was also clearly a contributing factor in the flash crash event of May 6, 2010.&quot;However, other researchers have reached a different conclusion. One 2010 study found that HFT did not significantly alter trading inventory during the Flash Crash. Some algorithmic trading ahead of index fund rebalancing transfers profits from investors.</span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c16 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><p class="c9 c13"><span class="c11"></span></p><h3 class="c23 c31 c95" id="h.5aizf42sxay3"><span class="c77"></span></h3><h1 class="c23 c31 c63" id="h.6iew2qmz0f0d"><span class="c22"></span></h1><h1 class="c63 c23 c31" id="h.473ekbrr0lyg"><span class="c22"></span></h1><a id="t.c0d545a3db871c32fb48c6a9409a1ccbe5e17cae"></a><a id="t.10"></a><table class="c26"><tr class="c4"><td class="c70" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><h1 class="c23 c31 c97" id="h.1mdohv3hapfc"><span class="c22">Algorithmic trading Leaders</span></h1><a id="t.6f361b2825c1b75ea57824410fbaf981cc6a758a"></a><a id="t.11"></a><table class="c26"><tr class="c4"><td class="c21" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c9 c31 c94"><span class="c82">Algorithmic Equity strategies have consistently delivered the highest annualized returns over the past five years. They all outperformed the market&rsquo;s annualized gains of 18.5 percent by more than 20 percent a year.</span></p><a id="t.6d4558a3b2535392dfd66e5c926106f7af0acab1"></a><a id="t.12"></a><table class="c26"><tr class="c8"><td class="c53" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c20"><span class="c35">Strategy &#9650;</span></p></td><td class="c72" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c20"><span class="c35">1Q 2022 Net Returns (%)</span></p></td><td class="c85" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c20"><span class="c35">2021 Net Returns %</span></p></td><td c